{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013GN96BRpZTL2x3R9UdrvxC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough information to compile the security audit findings. Let me analyze what I found:\n\n**Deployment Configuration:**\n1. **`--watch-ingress-without-class=true` AND `--watch-ingress-without-class=false`** — There are two conflicting flags in the container args. The original deployment had `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` in the last-applied-configuration, but the live spec shows BOTH `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` AND `--watch-ingress-without-class=false`. The last one to be processed wins, so the effective value is `false`. \n\n2. **`readOnlyRootFilesystem: false`** — The controller runs with a writable root filesystem, expanding the attack surface if code execution is compromised.\n\n3. **`terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0`** — No grace period means in-flight requests could be abruptly terminated.\n\n4. **`automountServiceAccountToken: true`** — The service account token is automatically mounted, which the controller needs for API access but is still a consideration.\n\n5. **`hostPort: 80` and `hostPort: 443`** — The controller binds directly to host ports, exposing the service at the node level.\n\n6. **Tolerations for control-plane nodes** — The controller can schedule on control-plane nodes, which is unusual and risky since a compromised controller could directly access the control plane.\n\n7. **No resource limits** — Only requests are defined with no upper limits, allowing unbounded CPU and memory consumption.\n\n8. **Unused IngressClass resources** — There are IngressClass definitions referencing non-existent controllers in the cluster.\n\n9. **No default IngressClass** — None of the three IngressClass resources is marked as the default, and the logs show they're being ignored, which increases attack surface since someone could create Ingresses targeting these orphaned classes.\n\n10. **Empty ConfigMap** — The ingress-nginx-controller ConfigMap has no data, so critical security settings like SSL protocol restrictions, HSTS, and server token hiding aren't explicitly configured and rely on defaults.\n\n11. **Overly permissive RBAC** — The ClusterRole grants cluster-wide `list` and `watch` permissions on secrets, pods, endpoints, and namespaces, which is broader than necessary for the controller to function.\n\n12. **No Network Policies** — The ingress-nginx and demo namespaces lack any NetworkPolicy, allowing unrestricted pod-to-pod communication.\n\n13. **Missing Ingress configuration and TLS** — The demo namespace has no Ingress resources or TLS secrets configured, and the demo app runs without resource limits on an outdated busybox image.\n\n14. **LoadBalancer service in pending state** — The ingress-nginx-controller service is configured as LoadBalancer but has no external IP assigned, and I'm noticing discrepancies between the original controller arguments and what's currently running.\n\n15. **Controller flag override** — The `watch-ingress-without-class` flag was initially set to `true` but has been overridden to `false` through an additional argument, and the `publish-status-address=localhost` setting prevents ingress resources from getting real public IPs in their status field.\n\nNow I'm compiling the critical and high-severity findings into a structured report.\n\n**Summary of findings:**\n\nCRITICAL:\n- C1: Controller ClusterRole has cluster-wide `secrets` list/watch (reads all TLS secrets)\n\nHIGH:\n- H1: `readOnlyRootFilesystem: false` — writable container filesystem\n- H2: `hostPort` 80/443 bound directly on node — bypasses NetworkPolicy\n- H3: No NetworkPolicy in ingress-nginx or demo namespace\n- H4: Conflicting `--watch-ingress-without-class` flags (true then false) — configuration inconsistency\n\nMEDIUM:\n- M1: No resource limits on controller (only requests)\n- M2: `terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0` — abrupt pod termination\n- M3: Orphaned IngressClass resources (`ingress-1`, `ingress-2`) referencing non-existent controllers\n- M4: Empty ConfigMap — no explicit nginx security settings (server-tokens, ssl-protocols, HSTS, proxy-body-size)\n- M5: Controller tolerates master/control-plane taints — can run on control plane\n- M6: `--publish-status-address=localhost` — Ingress status not reflecting real external IP\n\nLOW:\n- L1: No default IngressClass configured\n- L2: No Ingress resources in demo namespace — app not actually exposed through nginx\n- L3: `automountServiceAccountToken: true` explicitly set (expected but worth noting)\n- L4: No TLS configured for demo app\n\nNow I'm creating the findings text and storing it as a ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1348,"cache_read_input_tokens":39770,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1348},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"73ea54e6-9d7e-4bde-95ae-683a42f206f2","uuid":"79b29f57-b3b0-4677-8080-503818d73f14","request_id":"req_011CcQ1dDg3aHwwsFn9USyPh"}
