{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013GN96BRpZTL2x3R9UdrvxC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Qjn1SLcPT281rNSKWacJfe","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n demo create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\n=============================================================\nINGRESS-NGINX SECURITY AUDIT FINDINGS\nCluster: karma-local-3  |  Date: 2026-06-25  |  Auditor: automated read-only scan\nController version: ingress-nginx v1.14.1 (nginx/1.27.1)\n=============================================================\n\n--- CRITICAL ---\n\n[C1] CLUSTER-WIDE SECRETS LIST/WATCH IN CLUSTERROLE\n  Resource: ClusterRole/ingress-nginx\n  The ingress-nginx ClusterRole grants list+watch on secrets across ALL\n  namespaces. A compromised controller process can enumerate every TLS\n  secret, service-account token, and opaque secret in the cluster.\n  Remediation: Restrict secret access to the ingress-nginx namespace\n  via a Role, or scope to only secrets with specific label selectors.\n\n--- HIGH ---\n\n[H1] WRITABLE ROOT FILESYSTEM\n  Resource: Deployment/ingress-nginx-controller, container=controller\n  securityContext.readOnlyRootFilesystem is false.\n  An attacker who achieves RCE in the controller can modify binaries or\n  drop payloads on the container's writable filesystem.\n  Remediation: Set readOnlyRootFilesystem: true and use emptyDir/tmpfs\n  mounts for the paths nginx must write to (/tmp, /var/run, etc.).\n\n[H2] HOST PORT BINDING ON NODES 80/443\n  Resource: Deployment/ingress-nginx-controller, ports http+https\n  hostPort: 80 and hostPort: 443 are set, binding the controller\n  directly to the node's primary network interface. Traffic arriving on\n  those host ports bypasses Kubernetes NetworkPolicy enforcement.\n  Remediation: Expose via a LoadBalancer or NodePort Service instead of\n  hostPort, then apply NetworkPolicy to the controller's pod selector.\n\n[H3] NO NETWORKPOLICY IN INGRESS-NGINX OR DEMO NAMESPACE\n  Namespaces: ingress-nginx, demo\n  Neither namespace has any NetworkPolicy. All pods can freely reach the\n  controller's admin port (10254/healthz) and any other pod in the\n  cluster. There is no ingress/egress isolation.\n  Remediation: Add deny-all-ingress base policies, then allow only\n  required flows (node→controller:80/443, controller→demo-app backends).\n\n[H4] CONFLICTING --watch-ingress-without-class FLAGS\n  Resource: Deployment/ingress-nginx-controller args\n  The live pod spec contains BOTH --watch-ingress-without-class=true\n  (from the original manifest) AND --watch-ingress-without-class=false\n  (appended after a patch). The last flag wins, so the effective value\n  is false; but the inconsistency indicates an out-of-band patch that\n  was not reconciled with the source manifest.\n  Remediation: Remove the duplicate; keep only the intended value.\n  Set to false to prevent the controller from claiming class-less\n  Ingress objects it does not own.\n\n--- MEDIUM ---\n\n[M1] NO RESOURCE LIMITS ON CONTROLLER\n  Resource: Deployment/ingress-nginx-controller, container=controller\n  Only requests (cpu:100m, memory:90Mi) are set; limits are absent.\n  A traffic spike or bug can cause the controller to consume unbounded\n  CPU and memory, starving other workloads on the same node.\n  Remediation: Add matching or higher limits (e.g. cpu:500m, memory:256Mi).\n\n[M2] TERMINATION GRACE PERIOD IS ZERO\n  Resource: Deployment/ingress-nginx-controller\n  terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0 means the pod is SIGKILLed\n  immediately on deletion, dropping all in-flight TCP connections without\n  allowing the /wait-shutdown preStop hook to drain gracefully.\n  Remediation: Set terminationGracePeriodSeconds to 30 (or the p99\n  request duration) so the preStop hook can complete.\n\n[M3] ORPHANED INGRESSCLASS RESOURCES\n  Resources: IngressClass/ingress-1, IngressClass/ingress-2\n  Both reference controllers (k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1, -2) that do not\n  exist in the cluster. The logs confirm they are silently ignored.\n  Orphaned classes widen the attack surface: any Ingress targeting them\n  is silently unrouted, and a future deployment with those controller IDs\n  would immediately claim those Ingresses.\n  Remediation: Delete ingress-1 and ingress-2 if they are not needed.\n\n[M4] EMPTY CONTROLLER CONFIGMAP — NO EXPLICIT SECURITY SETTINGS\n  Resource: ConfigMap/ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller (data: null)\n  All nginx security settings fall back to upstream defaults.\n  Notable omissions:\n    - server-tokens not set to \"false\" (nginx version exposed in headers)\n    - ssl-protocols not pinned (should be \"TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3\")\n    - hsts not enabled\n    - proxy-body-size not set (default 1m; may be too large or too small)\n    - hide-headers not configured (server/x-powered-by not suppressed)\n  Remediation: Populate the ConfigMap with explicit values for the above.\n\n[M5] CONTROLLER TOLERATES MASTER/CONTROL-PLANE TAINTS\n  Resource: Deployment/ingress-nginx-controller tolerations\n  Tolerations for node-role.kubernetes.io/master and\n  node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane with NoSchedule are set.\n  If a nodeSelector or anti-affinity is not enforced, the controller\n  could be scheduled onto control-plane nodes, co-locating with etcd and\n  the API server.\n  Remediation: Remove the master/control-plane tolerations unless the\n  cluster topology explicitly requires it.\n\n[M6] --publish-status-address=localhost\n  Resource: Deployment/ingress-nginx-controller args\n  The controller advertises localhost as the external address for Ingress\n  status. Real clients cannot use this address; Ingress .status fields\n  will report 127.0.0.1, masking whether traffic is actually reachable.\n  Remediation: Set to the real load-balancer IP or hostname, or remove\n  the flag and let the controller derive it from the Service status.\n\n--- LOW ---\n\n[L1] NO DEFAULT INGRESSCLASS\n  Resources: IngressClass/nginx, IngressClass/ingress-1, IngressClass/ingress-2\n  None of the three IngressClass resources carries the annotation\n  ingressclass.kubernetes.io/is-default-class: \"true\".\n  Ingress resources without an explicit ingressClassName will not be\n  claimed by any controller.\n  Remediation: Annotate IngressClass/nginx as the default if intended.\n\n[L2] NO INGRESS RESOURCES IN DEMO NAMESPACE\n  Namespace: demo\n  The demo-app Deployment and its busybox pod are running but there is\n  no Ingress resource, no Service of type ClusterIP/NodePort, and no\n  TLS secret in the demo namespace. The application is currently\n  unreachable through the ingress controller.\n  Remediation: Create a Service and an Ingress (with TLS) for demo-app.\n\n[L3] DEMO APP IMAGE HAS NO RESOURCE LIMITS\n  Resource: Deployment/demo/demo-app (busybox:1.36)\n  No requests or limits defined. The demo container may starve the node.\n  Remediation: Set appropriate requests and limits.\n\n[L4] SERVICE ACCOUNT TOKEN AUTO-MOUNTED\n  Resource: ServiceAccount/ingress-nginx (automountServiceAccountToken: true)\n  This is expected for controller operation but is noted for completeness.\n  If any controller feature that requires API access is disabled, the\n  mount should be set to false to reduce the credential exposure window.\n\n=============================================================\nSUMMARY\n  Critical : 1\n  High     : 4\n  Medium   : 6\n  Low      : 4\n  Total    : 15 findings\n=============================================================\nFINDINGS\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap in demo namespace with findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1348,"cache_read_input_tokens":39770,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1348},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference